text: Eh...  The Jim Carrey movie wasn't that good anyway, and even for someone like me who is not a fan of Illumination, this definitely looks like an improvement over that film.  But my biggest question is, why do Dr. Seuss' books constantly get made into movies when the original books and TV specials don't need fixing.  Not everything was a classic, but they all had great levels of passion and surprisingly complex and universal morals.  All the movies do is just take all of that away and just replace with every family movie cliche meant to appeal to the lowest common denominator (like adding rap songs or Captain Planet straw man villains in The Lorax, or anime references in Horton, or all the needless and painful adult jokes in The Cat of the The Grinch  If you like any of the Dr. Seuss movies and/or are excited to see this one (or not, because just like The Mummy where people will constantly think of the Brendan Fraser one as the original due to the Tom Cruise movie, people will constantly think the Jim Carrey Grinch is the original instead of the Chuck Jones cartoon), that's absolutely fine with me, everyone gets excited over different things.  Just don't consider me part of that chorus of people.  I could be wrong and the movie could totally catch me off guard and actually be good, but I'm not holding out hope.

text: Okay, Dr. Seuss's Grinch has always been a sort of fairy-tale telling of the story of Grendel, with a twist for a happy ending.  ((Guy lives on a mountain, he's got neighbors in the valley that are too loud, he goes down and busts up their stuff.))  And as a Christian bonus it was because of the Christmas spirit. But this feels more like they're following a cue from John Gardner. I honestly don't know which author should get more credit. Obviously Seuss came first in '57, then Gardner in '71, but which story is going to show?

Illumination Studios is a company that prides itself in milking money out of films they know people will see while putting the least amount of work into their films. text: This film raises the very important question...    WHY?  The story, and redemption, has been told in animation, with one totally unnecessary live action film remake.  The story made clear that the Grinch was completely anti-social until AFTER his redemption.  So, if this is a "prequel", it makes no sense for him to be interacting with Whoville or its residents in ANY form (other than spying through his telescope).  And, if it's a sequel,  it COMPLETELY makes no sense, as the Grinch had been redeemed.  Oh, but we have all these computers to use (spitting in the eye of all the talented animators that produced the TIMELESS original...  It's Benedict Cumberbatch, so, is Mindy Lou going to yell, "GRIIIIIIINNNNNNCH!" at the camera?  Fuck you, Universal...

Eh? To me? But i still enjoy this for what it is.

text: Can Illumination just die as a company? And can all the talented and people who care about their craft be sent over to Disney and Pixar? All three movies they proudly mention are fucking awful.  Seriously, even though I enjoyed Sing as mindless entertainment, I know it's garbage and good god Secret Life of Pets is up their with The good Dinosaur as a bomb fest. I was so angry when I found out all the good and funny scenes were in the trailer. Nice bait.  Did you know that the late Dr. Seusses  wife found The Cat in the Hat with Michael Meyers to be so appaling that she banned any future live action films? Hollywood got around this by making them all CGI.  The Grinch got very mixed reviews (I personally like that movie, because even with the adult humor, the original point was still there even with the added idea of saying the towns people were greedy and the speech about averice.) Not a great movie, but CITH made me angry. The violent humor where he cuts off his tale, the overtly raunchy humor of oogling over the mom just ... no.  The lorax is a joke. Only reason the boy cared was to get in the pants of a girl old enough to be his baby sitter. And in the end, the trees were yet another commodity to oogle at. There was no intrinsic understanding of what the Oncler did and the possibility that maybe the tree in the last seed might never grow. Also the towns people were fine. There was no proverty and no one who could not afford clean air. So there was no actual conflict or reason to need trees. They were just pretty and they wanted them because they were rare.
author: Vixx Celacea

text: One more rant. Using Happy as the joke song  completely shows that they have no idea the point of that song itself. It's about being okay in hard times, not a mildless it's a small world smile on my face type song. His hide out is so clean. He's also genuinely just a mean person who's selfish. The Grinch was either born being miserable and depressed or in the live action one at least they tried to give a reason he was that way.  The Grinch also never came down to town. Not that I'm saying people shouldn't experiment with different takes, but this particular one kinda defeats whom the Grinch is. He genuinely hates the who's, he wants them all to be sad and miserable as he is. Being a troll in their town is not that.

text: Why remakeing The Grinch is a bad idea:  1) You can't live up to the original-  Sorry, you just can't. Regardless of how good the movie turns out people will compare it to the original and unless this remake is literally the best movie in the world, people will hate it.  2) remakes are typically bad quality-  Those Disney movie remakes -  tolerated. Ghostbusters remake - bad. Who could forget the 2000 Grinch remake? - Very VERY bad. Not all remakes are bad, but come on, but there is an undeniable trend.  3) No one wanted it  Seriously, if you think there was a large majority of people saying "oh the original Grinch was good, but what I REALLY want is a remake" then you are sorely mistaken. The only reason people watch half of these silly movies is because they recognize the characters. Look at the Emoji Movie, it relied on people just knowing what an emoji is and it ... Netted $25.65 million on its opening weekend?...  ...Whelp looks like I'm wrong. If the Emoji Movie can net $25.65 million on its opening weekend then anything can happen. Don't mind me, I'm just going to find a very high cliff to jump off of...

text: Ok this movie hasn‚Äôt even been released yet and I have 3 problems here.  Problem 1. The jokes aren‚Äôt funny just stupid. Come on Illumination. You guys wrote the Despicable Me movies. You can be funny. These movies are proof of that.  Problem 2. It‚Äôs totally dated with the music and stupid humor. One of the reasons the first movie was such a classic is how timeless it was. If I didn‚Äôt know it was from 1966 I would‚Äôve guessed 50s 70s or maybe even the 80s. It could‚Äôve taken place in a number of decades. With this, it screams 2010s. If we looked back at this in 20 or 30 years, we would be able to tell it‚Äôs from the 2010s. Being dated doesn‚Äôt do any justice to adapt the original book, nor match up to the first movie.  Problem 3. This movie has no reason to exist. We already have 2 movies of this. One was perfect and the other was........not so perfect. What‚Äôs the point of making another one when we already have an animated movie that‚Äôs perfectly fine? I feel like it‚Äôs only being made just to have a CGI version. text: I know the Jim Carrey film is a favorite to younger people, but I thought it was a mess. I was raised on the original animated TV special and still love it! I'm actually in favor of a new animated film, but this doesn't look right. The Grinch looks too cute, and his voice does not sound like a crotchety old man, it sounds like a 20-year-old. Also, we don't need modern pop culture references like that stupid "Happy" song - The Grinch is a timeless story and shouldn't date itself. Lastly, what the hell was that figure skating thing all about? Ugh. Well, if today's kids enjoy it, good for them.

text: This movie is a total disappointment. Trash. Trash. Trash. Worst: recycled trash. Disney no longer respects its viewers, let alone the source material.   Don‚Äôt go see it. Stream it illegally if you want. Either way, It‚Äôs a waste of time and money. I can promise you that in one year‚Äôs time, you will be seeing the 2000 version over this.   The characters are one dimensional and the same as every other Disney film.   Cindy Low Who? You mean the annoying Despicable Me girl whose kink is a Fluffy Pony‚Äîponytail and all. The Grinch? You mean Mr. ‚ÄúI lost my family, I am an orphan, was a good guy but loneliness made me sad and now I hate everyone and especially Christmas‚Äù. No! No! No!   The Grinch‚Äôs redemption in the original story had a huge impact because he was mean, not because he was a broken soul who needed the unconditional love from a little girl. Disney neutered the Grinch!! In this story, the Grinch had no balls to be mean. All the evil we ever get from him is in the trailer. Talk about spoiler alert!!!   The Moose? You might be wondering what I am talking about. You get my point.   The Mom and the festive guy who says he is the Grinch‚Äôs best friend. Did any of you get trailer trash and stereotypical black guy vibes?   Max. He was good hearted in the original; he is good hearted here. This is the only redeemable quality.  The gang of kids. Unnecessary.   You have been warned, Merry Christmas.

text: I feel that this movie was loyal to the book and the original 1966 animated version! They didn't change who the character's were and they didn't change the main plot of the story. Instead, they added more characters to contribute to the good story telling, a proper motivation for not only the grinch, but for the other characters as well, and an entire road of character development! It all made sence! We didn't have an unnecessary love story and we most certainly did not have bad behaving whos and sex jokes. The Grinch was decent, not gross and evil. You can argue that Ted Geisel's Grinch is supposed to be evil, but looking back, The original grinch didn't even interact with the whos! He just hated all the noise they would make. He didn't burn down trees or eat glass. Sure he did abuse his dog, but after his heart grew three sizes bigger, he actually treated his dog fairly! We could see this is the two other books Dr.Seuss wrote tittled "I am Max" and "I am Cindy Lou who". They happen right after Christmas. Some are mad that they took the abusive aspect away from him, but hey! If Jim Carrey's movie could change and rearrange everything then I'm pretty sure this shouldn't bother most people. I must say the interaction between the Grinch and the animals in this film were quite fun to watch!   In all honesty, Dr.Seuss made one dimensional character's who were only meant to convey a message. Of course I'm not saying Jim Carrey's is bad or you should not like it, but if we are going to start comparing carrey's to Cumberbatch's grinch then we need to set the two beside each other. This movie made sence while the other didn't.   The atmosphere, animation and music we see in this film is simply candy to one's ears and eyes and the comedy was actually funny! This may be the same studio who cursed us with fart jokes in every one of their films like the minions or Sing, but for once it seemed like they actually cared about the quality of their movie! Now that alone deserves to be appreciated.   My only conclusion as to why people didn't enjoy this grinch so much is because it was mostly directed towards a younger audience. It was soft. It didn't have that spark of weirdness. Jim Carrey's had adult jokes and creepy acting which the older audiences enjoyed a lot (12 and up)! It explains why most people found it boring, but bashing on it endlessy for being more decent is unacceptable. It ruins everyone's fun.   I enjoyed this Grinch a lot. It has so much for us to breathe in, yet it's still loyal to Ted Geisel's book and animated short. It's perfect.
